<td><a href="/wiki/Scientific_method#Experiments" title="Scientific method">Test and experiment</a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>In Pólya's view, <i>understanding</i> involves restating unfamiliar definitions in your own words, resorting to geometrical figures, and questioning what we know and do not know already; <i>analysis</i>, which Pólya takes from <a href="/wiki/Pappus_of_Alexandria" title="Pappus of Alexandria">Pappus</a><sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66" title=""><span>[</span>67<span>]</span></a></sup>, involves free and heuristic construction of plausible arguments, working backward from the goal, and devising a plan for constructing the proof; <i>synthesis</i> is the strict <a href="/wiki/Euclid" title="Euclid">Euclidean</a> exposition of step-by-step details<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67" title=""><span>[</span>68<span>]</span></a></sup> of the proof; <i>review</i> involves reconsidering and re-examining the result and the path taken to it.</p>
